{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CFUZFzwbJs1vQuNF7qxccB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior for the migration runner system.\n\n**Behavior 1: Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about sorting/ordering logic. The core question is whether the sorting algorithm correctly handles numeric prefixes (e.g., 1, 2, 10 vs lexicographic ordering where 10 < 2). This could be a pure unit test of the sorting function.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed to test sorting logic.\n- MOCK-HIDE: If we mock the file discovery, we might hide issues. But the sorting itself is a pure function.\n\n\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThe sorting logic itself is a pure function that can be tested at the unit level, but the real failure mode only surfaces when migrations are actually discovered and applied to the database in the wrong order. So I need both unit tests for the parsing and sorting, plus integration tests with real files to verify the end-to-end behavior.\n\nFor the second behavior around idempotency, the issue is that the runner needs to check the `_migrations` table before re-executing, which means I need a real PostgreSQL database to verify that check actually prevents duplicate runs.\n\nThe third behavior about rollback on failure requires actual transaction semantics from PostgreSQL—mocking the connection would hide whether rollback truly works, so this also needs integration testing with a real database.\n\nFor the fourth behavior around concurrent instances, I'm starting to think about what happens when two runners hit the same database simultaneously. access and locking. The failure only manifests with real concurrent processes.\n- REAL-INFRA: Requires real concurrent processes (subprocess) and real PostgreSQL advisory locks or similar. This is System level.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Any mock of locking would hide the real failure.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- MULTI-STEP: Involves multiple concurrent process interactions.\n\nThis is System level - requires running actual concurrent processes against a real database. The concurrency/locking behavior cannot be tested at Integration level with a single process.\n\n**Behavior 5: On the very first run against a fresh database, the `_migrations` table is created before any migration file is applied.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This requires verifying the bootstrap/initialization sequence against a real DB.\n- REAL-INFRA: Needs a real PostgreSQL to verify the table creation happens.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Mocking would hide whether table creation actually works.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nIntegration level - needs a real database but doesn't require subprocess concurrency.\n\nNow I'm assigning test levels to each behavior. Ordering should be Integration since it needs the full pipeline against a real database to verify migrations apply in the correct sequence, though the sorting logic itself could be Unit tested. Idempotency is clearly Integration - I need to check the actual database state to confirm repeated runs don't cause issues. Rollback on failure also lands in Integration because it depends on real PostgreSQL transactions, though there's some System-level complexity around transaction handling.\n\nConcurrent safety is definitely System level since it requires actual concurrent processes interacting with the database simultaneously. Bootstrap table creation is Integration - it needs a fresh database state but doesn't require concurrency.\n\nLet me reconsider the first behavior more carefully. The core question is whether I can test \"migrations are applied in ascending numeric order\" purely at the Unit level. The sorting function itself is testable as a Unit, but verifying that the execution pipeline actually uses that sorted order requires running the full system against a real database. The real failure mode would be if filenames get sorted lexicographically instead of numerically.\n\nI could mock the database adapter to record the order of execution calls without needing a real database, which would catch the sorting bug. That makes Unit testing viable for this behavior at around 0.30 confidence, with Integration at 0.60 since you'd still want to verify it works end-to-end.\n\nFor the rollback behavior, PostgreSQL transaction rollback is genuinely database-specific behavior that can't be unit tested. Integration is the minimum viable level. The question is whether the code correctly calls ROLLBACK on failure, which depends on how the Node.js pg client handles errors.\n\nConcurrency with advisory locks is trickier. You could spawn multiple async calls within a single test process against a real database, but the issue description mentions separate processes, which suggests the real failure mode involves cross-process locking. To catch OS-level process isolation issues, you'd need System-level testing with actual subprocesses. Integration testing with in-process async concurrency might miss those edge cases.\n\nFor the transaction rollback behavior, I need a real PostgreSQL connection to verify that partial changes actually get rolled back when a migration fails partway through. Integration is sufficient for that.\n\nSo my final assessment: Integration for sorting and application order, idempotency checks, and transaction rollback semantics; System for concurrent process locking; and Integration for bootstrap behavior against a fresh database.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9538,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9538},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"278a3560-dec2-4c80-ae3f-265bd0f80228","uuid":"cfdba4ba-91a7-4881-80d1-77cb6b7